result.execSummary:
The defendant Tiger A.F. Glynn was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Criminal Damage to Property, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Tiger A.F. Glynn in court with attorney Matthew J Pribyl. Raymond Pelrine appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Court reviews charges, max. penalties, elements. Defendant enters no contest plea to Counts 1, 2, 3, 4. Court questions Defendant on rights, finds pleas made freely and voluntarily, accepts pleas, and finds Defendant guilty of Counts 1, 2, 3, 4. State/Defense make joint sentencing recommendations. Bond no longer in effect.

Defendant Tiger A.F. Glynn in court with attorney Grant Alexander Erickson. Raymond Pelrine appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Todd Glynn appeared by phone. Court reviews previous activity. Mr. Glynn clarifies, requests that money be returned after sentencing, not at this time. Court questions State, who did receive copy of letter. Atty Erickson advises of limited capacity of his representation, reviewed State's copy of letter prior to hearing. State advises of conversation his VW Coordinator had with Mr. Glynn this morning, advises of statute requiring that posted bond money be applied to financial obligations. Atty Erickson responds, presents argument for signature bond should Court decide to return the money to Mr. Glynn. State presents argument against conversion of bond to signature. Court agrees, will not convert bond, advises Mr. Glynn that he does not have the power to return the bond after sentencing, questions Mr. Glynn whether he wants money back now or not. Mr. Glynn does not want Defendant back in jail.
